      "src/bidding/domain/events.ts — BidWindowOpened, BidClaimed, BidWindowExpired, AutoAssigned domain events",
      "src/bidding/infrastructure/redis/bid-claim.lua — Atomic Lua script: check bid status is OPEN, check courier is eligible, SET winner if unset, return result",
      "src/bidding/infrastructure/redis/BidWindowRepository.ts — Redis-backed repository: create window, claim bid (via Lua), read state, manage TTLs",
      "src/bidding/application/BidWindowManager.ts — Orchestrator: handles OrderPlaced, creates bid window, triggers fan-out, handles timeout",
      "src/bidding/application/BidProcessor.ts — Thin service: validates input, delegates to repository.claim(), publishes result events",
      "src/gateway/CourierWebSocketGateway.ts — WebSocket server partitioned by zone, manages connections, handles fan-out and acceptance forwarding",
      "src/gateway/ConnectionRegistry.ts — Maps courierId → WebSocket connection, supports zone-based lookup for fan-out",
      "src/scheduler/TimeoutScheduler.ts — Polls Redis sorted set for expired bid windows, triggers auto-assignment",
      "src/eligibility/CourierEligibilityService.ts — Query service: returns eligible couriers for a zone with ratings",
      "src/assignment/AssignmentService.ts — Consumes BidClaimed/AutoAssigned events, persists assignment, updates order and courier state",
      "infrastructure/redis/docker-compose.yml — Redis Sentinel setup for local development",
      "tests/bidding/bid-claim-atomicity.test.ts — Concurrent acceptance test: spawn 30 parallel claim attempts, verify exactly 1 winner"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Use the aggregate pattern for BidWindow — all state transitions go through the aggregate root. Use domain events for cross-context communication. Use the repository pattern to abstract Redis operations behind a clean interface. The Lua script is an infrastructure detail hidden behind the repository. Use dependency injection throughout for testability. For the WebSocket gateway, use the adapter pattern to decouple transport from business logic.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT use application-level locks (mutexes, semaphores) for bid claiming — they don't work across multiple server instances. The Redis Lua script IS the lock.",
      "DO NOT store bid window state in application memory — it must be in Redis for crash recovery and multi-instance consistency.",
      "DO NOT use Redis WATCH/MULTI/EXEC for the atomic claim — Lua scripts are simpler and more reliable for this use case since WATCH can fail under high contention.",
      "DO NOT fan out notifications synchronously in the bid window creation path — use async pub/sub to avoid blocking the bid window manager.",
      "DO NOT rely on Redis key expiry events (keyspace notifications) as the primary timeout mechanism — they are not guaranteed to fire exactly on time. Use sorted set polling instead.",
      "DO NOT allow a courier to participate in multiple active bid windows simultaneously without explicit handling — they could win two jobs at once. Track active bids per courier."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 88,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Atomic bid claiming via Redis Lua script — this is a well-proven pattern for exactly-once semantics",
      "WebSocket for real-time courier communication — standard approach for mobile real-time apps",
